                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 400</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Pacheco<br/>(Coauthors: Assembly Members Ahrens, Alanis, Ramos, and Michelle Rodriguez)<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 04, 2025</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;">An act to add and repeal Section 13514.7 of the Penal Code, relating to the Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training.</span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 400, Pacheco.
                          Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training: police canines.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training within the Department of Justice and requires the commission to, among other things, develop and disseminate guidelines for all peace officers in California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require, on or before July 1, 2028, the commission to study and issue recommendations to the Legislature on the use of canines by law enforcement. The bill would require the commission to consider in its recommendations, among other things, instances of appropriate patrol use with a canine, as specified, and instances of appropriate use with a canine for detection, as specified. The bill would repeal
			 these provisions on July 1, 2031.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.7687670565028163"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> Section 13514.7 is added to the Penal Code, to read:</div><div><div id="id_27003EC3-EB85-4DEE-B363-E6B03FAB7551"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">13514.7.</h6> (a) On or before July 1, 2028, the Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training shall study and issue recommendations to the Legislature on the use of canines by law enforcement. The commission shall consider all of the following in its recommendations:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) The use of canines by law enforcement personnel is of important concern to the community and law enforcement and law enforcement should safeguard the life, dignity, and liberty of all persons, without prejudice to anyone.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Officers shall carry out duties, including use of force with respect to canines, in a manner that is fair and unbiased.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Instances of appropriate patrol use with a canine, including standards for obedience, search, apprehension, and handler protection.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Instances of appropriate use with a canine for detection, including standards for control, alert, and odor detection.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Factors for evaluating and reviewing all canine use of force incidents.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Other considerations that will keep the public, the handler, and the canine safe, including how to provide a warning to a suspect within a
						deployment area upon the potential release of a canine.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) A report to be submitted pursuant to subdivision (a) shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795 of the Government Code.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Pursuant to Section 10231.5 of the Government Code, this section is repealed on July 1, 2031.</div></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
